#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:4
msgid ""
"TITLE:\t\tXMAIL LFS VERSION:\t3.3, 4.0 and CVS AUTHOR:\t\tRichard Downing "
"<richard.downing@bcs.org.uk>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:7
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"SYNOPSIS:\n"
"\tHow to set up xmail-1.11 instead of sendmail, postfix, qmail at al.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:13
msgid ""
"HINT: This hint explains how to build and set up xmail on your LFS "
"system. Xmail, by Davide Libenzi, is a single server which replaces, say, "
"sendmail+qpopper+fetchmail, or as I used on an LFS system long ago, "
"postfix+procmail+fetchmail+qpopper."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:17
msgid ""
"And since I know that this hint is linked to from the Xmail website, I "
"should add for Xmail readers that LFS = Linux From Scratch - the best way to "
"learn Linux and Unix, by building one from sources: Visit"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:19
#, no-wrap
msgid "\thttp://www.linuxfromscratch.org\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:22
msgid ""
"Why Xmail? Basically: why install three or four packages when one will do "
"the job?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:28
msgid ""
"The big problem with xmail-1.11 is that Davide hasn't got around to writing "
"either a configure script or an installation script.  This presents just a "
"few interesting opportunities for error, especially if you are still a bit "
"unix-challenged.  However once the package is installed it appears to work "
"well and do what it is advertised to do."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:30
msgid "There is an active, knowledgable, but a bit busy, mailing list."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:34
msgid ""
"I have used these instructions on a number of LFS builds, including my "
"latest, An LFS CVS20021105 with glibc-2.3.1/gcc-3.2.1, with complete "
"success."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:36
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Obtain and Unpack the package.\n"
"------------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:39
msgid "Download the package from: http://www.xmailserver.org"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:44
msgid ""
"It's a .tar.gz, so unpack in the usual way, and cd xmail-1.11.  (Note: I've "
"used this process to build Xmail's since version 1.8, so I expect they will "
"still work for the next few releases - let me know if they let you down or "
"need clarifying)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:47
msgid ""
"Start by checking out the documentation in the docs directory: Readme.html "
"or Readme.txt is the only manual!"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:49
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Build the executables.\n"
"----------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:51
msgid "Choose your Makefile depending on the architecture of your LFS machine:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:55
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\tmake -f Makefile.lnx  - for an i86 box\n"
"\tmake -f Makefile.slx  - for a SPARC\n"
"\tmake -f Makefile.plx  - for a PPC\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:57
msgid "(Note I only have experience with i86)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:59
msgid "You can strip the executables now if space is an issue."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:62
msgid ""
"This will build Xmail and it's toolset, this includes a SysV init script "
"which works on a LFS system, but more on that later."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:64
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Install Xmail.\n"
"--------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:67
msgid "This is where the fun comes.  Su to root if you are not already."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:70
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\tcp -a MailRoot /var\n"
"\tchmod 700 /var/MailRoot\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:73
msgid ""
"Most of XMail's files are held in /var/MailRoot, which is only accessable by "
"root."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:75
#, no-wrap
msgid "\tcp XMail XMCrypt MkUsers sendmail /var/MailRoot/bin\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:78
msgid ""
"However the CtrlClnt binary needs to be accessible to whoever is going to "
"administer the xmail system:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:80
#, no-wrap
msgid "\tcp CtrlClnt /usr/bin\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:82
msgid "Copy the Manual to appropriate places:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:85
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\tcp -p Readme.txt /usr/share/xmail/Manual.txt\n"
"\tcp    Readme.html /usr/share/xmail/Manual.html\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:87
msgid "If you plan to use Davide's init script copy it now:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:89
#, no-wrap
msgid "\tcp xmail /etc/rc.d/init.d\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:91
msgid "Or create a more LFS-like script, such as:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:93
msgid "cat > /etc/rc.d/init.d/xmail << \"EOF\""
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:96
msgid "#!/bin/bash # Begin $rc_base/init.d/XMail"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:102
msgid ""
"# Based on sysklogd script from LFS-3.1 and earlier.  # Rewritten by Gerard "
"Beekmans - gerard@linuxfromscratch.org # # XMail init script by Richard A "
"Downing - richard.downing@bcs.org.uk # using LFS template and XMail-1.11 "
"skeleton."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:105
msgid "source /etc/sysconfig/rc source $rc_functions"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:109
msgid ""
"export MAIL_ROOT=/var/MailRoot export MAIL_CMD_LINE=\"-Qn 2 -Pl -Sl -Fl -Cl "
"-Ll\" PATH=$XMAIL_ROOT/bin:$PATH"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:115
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"case \"$1\" in\n"
"\tstart)\n"
"\t\techo \"Starting XMail ...\"\n"
"\t\tloadproc $MAIL_ROOT/bin/XMail\n"
"\t\t;;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:120
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\tstop)\n"
"\t\techo \"Stopping XMail ...\"\n"
"\t\tkillproc XMail\n"
"\t\t;;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:125
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\treload)\n"
"\t\techo \"Reloading XMail ...\"\n"
"\t\treloadproc XMail\n"
"\t\t;;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:131
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\trestart)\n"
"\t\t$0 stop\n"
"\t\tsleep 1\n"
"\t\t$0 start\n"
"\t\t;;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:135
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\tstatus)\n"
"\t\tstatusproc XMail\n"
"\t\t;;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:141
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\t*)\n"
"\t\techo \"Usage: $0 {start|stop|reload|restart|status}\"\n"
"\t\texit 1\n"
"\t\t;;\n"
"esac\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:144
msgid "# End $rc_base/init.d/XMail EOF"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:147
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Replace or create a sendmail script\n"
"-----------------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:152
msgid ""
"If your MUA (Kmail, for instance) interfaces (when sending mail) with the "
"MTA using SMTP you can skip this step entirely, but some MUA's need a "
"sendmail script which you can create like this."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:155
msgid ""
"The sendmail executable needs the SETGUID bit set to run as root and this "
"might be a security hole."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:158
msgid ""
"If you already have a sendmail script or program, move it aside (your's "
"might be in /usr/bin or elsewhere):"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:160
#, no-wrap
msgid "\tmv /usr/sbin/sendmail /usr/sbin/sendmail.orig\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:163
msgid ""
"Copy Xmail's sendmail executable to an appropriate place, and set it's "
"SETUID bit so that it runs as root."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:166
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\tcp sendmail /usr/sbin/sendmail.xmail\n"
"\tchmod +s /usr/sbin/sendmail.xmail\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:168
msgid "And create a sendmail script to set the environment and call the executable:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:173
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\tcat > /usr/sbin/sendmail << \"EOF\"\n"
"\t#!/bin/bash\n"
"\t# This script sets the environment for XMail's sendmail and then calls "
"it.\n"
"\t# The script exists so that software that expects sendmail can use "
"XMail.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:180
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\tif [ -z $MAIL_ROOT ]; then\n"
"        export MAIL_ROOT=/var/MailRoot\n"
"\tfi\n"
"\t/usr/sbin/sendmail.xmail $*\n"
"\t# End /usr/sbin/sendmail\n"
"\tEOF\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:182
#, no-wrap
msgid "\tchmod +x /usr/sbin/sendmail\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:184
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Configure Xmail's server.tab.\n"
"-----------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:191
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"It's important to note that all of xmail's configuration files use the "
"'tab'\n"
"character as a separator character - don't use spaces or extra tabs, and "
"every \n"
"line, EVEN THE LAST ONE in a file must have a terminating <return>.   For "
"this \n"
"reason, apart from the following, I don't edit the tab files directly, "
"prefering\n"
"the control interface, see later.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:195
msgid ""
"Use your favourite text editor to edit /var/MailRoot/server.tab for your "
"domain name, and set the names of the user's who will get error and "
"postmaster messages."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:198
msgid ""
"The files as delivered contain a reasonable starting point with a domain "
"called 'xmailserver.test' which you can use to try things out if you want."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:202
msgid ""
"The server configuration variables are well described in part 12 of the "
"Manual (which you saved in /usr/share/xmail/Manual.txt !) - so check what "
"your situation needs.  My server.tab is:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:214
msgid ""
"\"RootDomain\"\t\"109bean.org.uk\" \"POP3Domain\"\t\"109bean.org.uk\" "
"\"PostMaster\"\t\"root@109bean.org.uk\" "
"\"ErrorsAdmin\"\t\"root@109bean.org.uk\" "
"\"DefaultSMTPGateways\"\t\"smtp.your-isp.com\" \"RemoveSpoolErrors\"\t\"0\" "
"\"MaxMTAOps\"\t\"16\" \"ReceivedHdrType\"\t\"0\" "
"\"FetchHdrTags\"\t\"+X-Deliver-To,+Received,To,Cc\" "
"\"Pop3SyncErrorAccount\"\t\"root@109bean.org.uk\" "
"\"DefaultSmtpPerms\"\t\"MRVZ\""
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:217
msgid ""
"(note: I have not registered 109bean.org.uk, as it's never seen outside of "
"my network)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:220
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Setup the domain.tab file to contain the name of your domain:\n"
"\t\"109bean.org.uk\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:225
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now set up a 'control' account, I called mine 'root'.  Choose a nice "
"complicated\n"
"password and find its encrypted form with XMCrypt, I'll use 'ciao' as an \n"
"example:\n"
"\t/var/MailRoot/bin/XMCrypt ciao\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:229
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now edit /var/MailRoot/ctrlaccounts.tab to read something like this, where "
"the \n"
"second element is the string that XMCrypt returned:\n"
"\t\"root\"\t\"060c040a\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:234
msgid ""
"Note the double-quotes are really there in the file and the separator IS a "
"single 'tab' and the line IS terminated with a <return>.  Wherever a 'tab' "
"file format calls for a password, it's an XMCrypt password that's needed - "
"this caused me a lot of problems!"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:236
msgid ""
"You will need at least one user set up in /var/MailRoot/mailusers.tab, and "
"while"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:241
msgid ""
"you are editing it delete the sample account for 'xmailuser', remember to "
"use XMCrypt to find your encrypted password."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:243
msgid "and that is sufficient to get XMail running."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:245
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Start XMail for the first time.\n"
"-------------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:248
msgid "Start XMail in debug mode with the following commands:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:251
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\texport MAIL_ROOT=/var/MailRoot\n"
"\t/var/MailRoot/bin/XMail -Md -Pl -Sl -Fl -Cl -Ll ...\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:255
msgid ""
"where the ... are any other command line switches you might want or need - "
"see part 19 of the Manual.  (By the way those switches end with a lower case "
"L - not obvious in some fonts!)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:261
msgid ""
"You will see the various XMail threads start up, and if all looks stable you "
"have a working XMail.  If you can start another terminal session, a second "
"xterm or login on another tty, then you can command XMail (see next session) "
"and watch the debugging output.  When you are happy, hit Ctrl-C and abort "
"the run, watching XMail shut down it's threads gracefully."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:263
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Setup the SysV init script.\n"
"---------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:266
msgid "Link the SysV init script as you see fit into the rc.d system, I set:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:275
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\tcd /etc/rc.d\n"
"\tln -s init.d/xmail rc0.d/K27xmail\n"
"\tln -s init.d/xmail rc1.d/K27xmail\n"
"\tln -s init.d/xmail rc2.d/K27xmail\n"
"\tln -s init.d/xmail rc6.d/K27xmail\n"
"\tln -s init.d/xmail rc3.d/S43xmail\n"
"\tln -s init.d/xmail rc4.d/S43xmail\n"
"\tln -s init.d/xmail rc5.d/S43xmail\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:277
msgid "although I actually do it with KDE3's SysV-Init editor."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:281
msgid ""
"The aim is to close xmail before the network goes down, but after any "
"activity which might cause mail activity, and to start xmail after the "
"network is up, but before starting anything that might generate mail (for "
"example: fcron)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:283
msgid "Now you can run the xmail daemon properly by issuing:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:285
msgid "/etc/rc.d/init.d/xmail start"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:290
msgid ""
"which will fork the daemon and display its process id (pid).  Now you can "
"set up your other accounts and the links to mail servers at your ISP, and "
"becuase you are asking XMail to do it for you, you are assured that the "
"setup will be self-consistent."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:292
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Setting up another user account.\n"
"--------------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:294
msgid "Type the following, you don't need to be 'root':"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:297
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\t/usr/bin/CtrlClnt -s 109bean.org.uk -u root -p ciao \\\n"
"\tuseradd 109bean.org.uk newuser newpassword U\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:300
msgid ""
"Of course, you need to substitute your domain name, Control Account and "
"password."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:303
msgid ""
"In these CtrlClnt (Control Client) commands you should NOT use MKCrypt-ed "
"passwords."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:308
msgid ""
"Once the user account(s) are set up, you can try sending mail between them "
"locally.  Set up your MUA, say Mutt or Kmail, to send via smtp "
"localhost:110, and receive by POP3 from '109bean.org.uk' or whatever your "
"domain is called, with the appropriate username and password as just setup."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:310
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Setting up a POP3 drop from your ISP.\n"
"-------------------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:314
msgid ""
"Assuming your ISP presents a simple unencrypted (old-fashioned) POP3 "
"service, you need to know your login name (you-at-isp) and password "
"(your-isp-pop-password)and the address of the POP3 server."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:318
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\t/usr/bin/CtrlClnt -s 109bean.org.uk -u root -p ciao \\\n"
"\tpoplnkadd 109bean.org.uk richard \\\n"
"\tpop3.isp.com you-at-isp your-isp-pop-password CLR\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:320
msgid ""
"This will set up an automatic synchonisation between XMail and your pop3 "
"account"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:326
msgid ""
"at pop3.isp.com, syncronising every 2 minutes (120 seconds).  To change the "
"synchronisation rate to, say, every 5 minutes, you need to edit the command "
"line switch -Yi 300 (300 seconds) in /etc/rc.d/init.d/xmail."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:328
msgid "If your ISP supports APOP authorisation substitute APOP for CLR above."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/xmail.txt:330
msgid "That's all I did, and it works for me.  Good luck."
msgstr ""
